<paragraph blockId="43.[806,1422,689,1139]" box="[806,996,689,710]" pageId="43" pageNumber="115">
<emphasis box="[806,996,689,710]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="115">Taxonomic notes</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="43.[806,1422,689,1139]" pageId="43" pageNumber="115">
Large species (
<quantity box="[976,1076,719,740]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3699999999999999" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" unit="mm" value="13.7">13.7 mm</quantity>
) with broad abdomen; similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray, 2012" authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[837,1015,749,771]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mozotalensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[837,1015,749,771]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="115">Q. mozotalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1022,1109,750,771]" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray, 2012" authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[1202,1331,749,771]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="solitaria" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1202,1331,749,771]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="115">Q. solitaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1337,1422,750,771]" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the facial hairs are white, the medial pollinose stripes of the scutum faintly reach the posterior margin of the scutum, the scutellum is wholly yellow haired and the pro- and mesofemur are extensively black, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray, 2012" authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[952,1130,902,924]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mozotalensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[952,1130,902,924]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="115">Q. mozotalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1137,1221,903,924]" pageId="43" pageNumber="115" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the facial hairs are golden yellow, the medial pollinose stripes of the scutum are narrower and do not reach the posterior margin of the scutum, the scutellum has scattered black hairs, and the pro- and mesofemur are extensively red. Various differences in the puparia of these two species, such as the body vestiture, validate these species concepts.
</paragraph>
